Great, here is the full Kubernetes startup path for your project from a clean terminal in the repo root.

1. Confirm prerequisites
- Docker Desktop is running
- Kubernetes is enabled in Docker Desktop
- kubectl points to docker-desktop

Commands:
kubectl config current-context
kubectl get nodes

2. Add local host mapping
- Add this line to your hosts file:
127.0.0.1 smart-healthcare.local

3. Set required environment variables in PowerShell
- Use real values, then run this in the same terminal session:

$env:AUTH_MONGODB_URI="your-auth-mongodb-uri"
$env:PATIENT_MONGODB_URI="your-patient-mongodb-uri"
$env:DOCTOR_MONGO_URI="your-doctor-mongodb-uri"
$env:APPOINTMENT_MONGODB_URI="your-appointment-mongodb-uri"
$env:JWT_SECRET="your-jwt-secret"
$env:JWT_EXPIRES_IN="7d"
$env:STRIPE_SECRET_KEY="your-stripe-secret-key"
$env:EMAIL_USER="your-email"
$env:EMAIL_APP_PASSWORD="your-email-app-password"
$env:EMAIL_PROVIDER="auto"
$env:EMAIL_FROM="your-email-or-sender"
$env:SENDGRID_API_KEY=""
$env:TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID=""
$env:TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN=""
$env:TWILIO_PHONE_NUMBER=""
$env:GEMINI_API_KEY=""

4. Create or update Kubernetes secrets
Command:
apply-k8s-secrets.ps1

5. Build all service images
Commands:
docker build -t frontend-image:latest .\frontend
docker build -t ai-symptom-checker-image:latest .\services\ai-symptom-checker
docker build -t auth-service-image:latest .\services\auth-service
docker build -t patient-service-image:latest .\services\patient-service
docker build -t doctor-service-image:latest .\services\doctor-service
docker build -t appointment-service-image:latest .\services\appointment-service
docker build -t payment-service-image:latest .\services\payment-service
docker build -t notification-service-image:latest .\services\notification-service

6. Deploy manifests
Command:
Get-ChildItem .\k8s\*.yaml | Where-Object { $_.Name -notlike "*.example.yaml" } | ForEach-Object { kubectl apply -f $_.FullName }

7. Restart all deployments once (good after fresh image builds)
Command:
kubectl get deployments -n default -o name | ForEach-Object { kubectl rollout restart $_ -n default }
kubectl get deployments -n default -o name | ForEach-Object { kubectl rollout status $_ -n default --timeout=300s }

8. Verify health
Commands:
kubectl get deployments -n default
kubectl get pods -n default -o wide
kubectl get svc -n default
kubectl get ingress -n default

9. Open app
- URL:
http://smart-healthcare.local

If you want, I can now run a full post-start smoke check for you (auth, doctor list, appointment create, and notification flow) and report exactly what passes/fails.